500|$|The first organized, {{large-scale}} propaganda campaigns were during World War I. Germany {{created the}} German <b>Information</b> <b>Bureau</b> to create pamphlets, books and other communications that {{were intended to}} support the justness of their cause, to encourage voluntary recruitment, to demonize the enemy and persuade America to remain neutral in the conflict. In response to learning about Germany's propaganda, the British created a war propaganda agency called the Wellington House in September 1914. Atrocity stories, both real and alleged, were used to incite hatred for the enemy, especially after the [...] "Rape of Belgium" [...] in 1915. France created a propaganda agency in 1914. Publicity in Australia led to a lift in the government's ban on military drafts. [...] Austria-Hungary used propaganda tactics to attack the credibility of Italy's leadership and its motives for war. Italy in-turn created the Padua Commission in 1918, which led Allied propaganda against Austria-Hungary.|$|E
