40|$|Consumer credit {{has shown}} strong growth in {{emerging}} and newly industrialised Asian economies in recent years. While credit card lending has helped smooth consumer spending and improved {{the profitability of}} financial institutions, it also represents {{a new source of}} risk. Preventing financial and macroeconomic instability associated with consumer lending requires policy makers to be confident that lenders have proper risk management systems in place and consumers have sustainable debt burdens. Public policy also needs to ensure that essential infrastructure for consumer credit is available and set up properly, such as credit <b>information</b> <b>bureaux</b> and personal debt workout systems. ...|$|R
40|$|Factoring is {{explicitly}} {{linked to the}} value of a supplier’s accounts receivable and receivables are sold, rather than collateralized, and factored receivables {{are not part of the}} estate of a bankrupt firm. Therefore, factoring may allow a high-risk supplier to transfer its credit risk to higher quality buyers. Empirical tests find that factoring is larger in countries with greater economic development and growth and developed credit <b>information</b> <b>bureaus.</b> “Reverse factoring ” may mitigate the problem of borrowers’ informational opacity if only receivables from high-quality buyers are factored. We illustrate the case of the Nafin reverse factoring program in Mexico...|$|R
